1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Stanford University

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Alright, so what is particle physics about?

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Particle physics is about particles.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:17,500
It's about the question, and

5
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:20,000
this is a very ancient question,

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:25,000
at least, I suspect, about 2500 years old,

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:27,000
is nature discrete?

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Discrete meaning to say, not that it's polite,

9
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
but that matter and substances and energy,

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,000
they didn't think about energy,

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,000
but they thought about matter.

12
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
That matter comes in discrete units,

13
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,000
in indivisible units,

14
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:50,000
which of course the Greeks called atom.

15
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
I'm told that the word atom means indivisible,

16
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,500
despite the fact that of course

17
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:56,000
we break up atoms all the time.

18
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:57,000
Nevertheless,

19
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
the origin of the word,

20
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:00,000
indivisible,

21
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:03,000
that all things in the universe

22
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
are made up out of something discrete.

23
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Let's call them particles.

24
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Particles is a good name for something discrete,

25
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,000
something indivisible.

26
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,000
That idea is, as I said, extremely ancient.

27
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
The opposite idea is also ancient.

28
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Again, I don't know precisely when it was first formulated,

29
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,500
I happen to remember a little more

30
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:31,000
about the history of the atomic idea,

31
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,000
that was, it doesn't matter who it is.

32
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Incidentally, do not trust my history,

33
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:39,000
not because I don't know the history,

34
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,500
but I sometimes tell the history

35
00:01:41,500 --> 00:01:44,000
in which I organize things logically,

36
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,000
rather than temporally.

37
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,000
So don't trust the time sequence that I tell you.

38
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
It often represents what I wish the time sequence was,

39
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,000
rather than what it actually was.

40
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
But it's good for being,

41
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,000
to present the logic of what happened,

42
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,000
to present it in a logically compelling way,

43
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
rather than a strict historical way.

44
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
In any case,

45
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:14,000
there were these characters who were the atomists,

46
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,000
and the opposite of them,

47
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:22,000
the people who thought that matter, material, and so forth,

48
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
was continuously distributed.

49
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,500
Continuously distributed means simply not

50
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,000
made up out of discrete elements,

51
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,000
but, I don't know what the right word is,

52
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
uniform, continuous is the right word,

53
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:38,000
a smear, as my grandmother would have said.

54
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:39,000
A smear.

55
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,500
Smeared out of a space in

56
00:02:41,500 --> 00:02:44,000
some uniform, continuous kind of way.

57
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
And we might call that the field theory of matter.

58
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Fields, what are fields?

59
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Fields are functions in space,

60
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:57,000
for example, they could be the density of material

61
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:01,000
in a given region of space.

62
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
They could be the electric and magnetic fields.

63
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Those are good examples.

64
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Electric and magnetic fields that

65
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
determine how charged particles move.

66
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
But the fields themselves, the electric and magnetic fields,

67
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,500
are things that we conceive of

68
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:18,000
as being uniformly distributed in space,

69
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
not in the form of particles.

70
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
And so,

71
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:28,000
perhaps, matter, liquids, solids, and so forth,

72
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,000
are also, in some sense, continuous,

73
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,000
just like the electromagnetic field.

74
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,000
That was the opposite idea.

75
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
The particle idea, the discrete idea,

76
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:43,000
had words like molecules, atoms, and so forth,

77
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
collisions, and particles.

78
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
The continuum idea, continuum is the right word,

79
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:56,000
the continuum idea had words like fields attached to it,

80
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:01,000
continuous fields of properties of various kinds.

81
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,000
Which turned out to be right?

82
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
In some sense, neither and both.

83
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,500
In some sense, neither and

84
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:11,000
both turned out to be right.

85
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,500
The subtleties of quantum mechanics got in the

86
00:04:14,500 --> 00:04:18,000
way of either of them being completely right,

87
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:18,500
but it also got in the way

88
00:04:18,500 --> 00:04:19,000
of either of them being completely right.

89
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
But it also got in the way

90
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
of either of them being completely wrong.

91
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Quantum mechanics is a subtle and difficult subject,

92
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:34,000
as are many of the preliminaries to particle physics.

93
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,500
I think I have taught all

94
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:37,000
of them by now several times,

95
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,000
and they do exist on the internet.

96
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
The internet lectures that I've given, they're out there.

97
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
And I advise you,

98
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
as I said, I will try to keep itself contained,

99
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
but I am going to assume to some extent

100
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
the knowledge that I have

101
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
taught previously in these classes.

102
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
It can be picked up off the internet very easily.

103
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
I don't know how to do it.

104
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
I couldn't do it for the life of me.

105
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
I can never access my own lectures.

106
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,000
But everybody else can do it.

107
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
And, well, the real reason is

108
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
I don't like looking at myself.

109
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
So I never do open my own lectures.

110
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:14,000
But they're out there.

111
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And they're fairly complete.

112
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
There are at least two

113
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
courses out there on quantum mechanics.

114
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:24,000
I think one on classical mechanics,

115
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:27,000
at least one on special

116
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
theory of relativity and electromagnetism.

117
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:34,000
So since I put that effort in,

118
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
I'm now going to try to draw on it,

119
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
not today, but in the future,

120
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
and use many of the

121
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
things that I have lectured about.

122
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Okay.

123
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
So, as I said,

124
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
the particle physics question is

125
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
whether nature is discrete or not.

126
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Let's just do a little bit of history,

127
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
which I will probably get wrong,

128
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:59,000
but that's at least chronologically.

129
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
To my knowledge, the first real evidence,

130
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
again, it's to my knowledge,

131
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
the first real evidence that matter was discrete

132
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
came, of course, from chemistry.

133
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,000
It didn't come from physics.

134
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
It came from chemistry.

135
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
The division between chemistry and physics

136
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,000
is a highly artificial one.

137
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,000
Chemistry is simply just the,

138
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
basically the physics of atoms and molecules.

139
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
But it came from the chemist,

140
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,000
John, John Dalton?

141
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:27,000
John, I think.

142
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
John Dalton,

143
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:34,000
who realized that the masses of chemicals,

144
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
the mass of a given number of molecules,

145
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
a given number of molecules,

146
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
now how he knew that he had

147
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
to deal with a given number of molecules

148
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,500
when he might be talking

149
00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:47,000
on the one hand of hydrogen,

150
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
the other hand of a carbon dioxide or something,

151
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:51,500
how he knew it was a given

152
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:53,000
number of molecules is itself a story.

153
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
Avogadro's name comes into it and so forth.

154
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:57,000
The word mole,

155
00:06:57,000 --> 00:06:59,000
not the creature that lives under the ground,

156
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:04,000
but the mole is Avogadro's number of molecules.

157
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,000
How they knew how many molecules,

158
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:07,000
they didn't know how many molecules,

159
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
but how they knew how to compare different substances

160
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,000
and say both of them

161
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:12,000
had the same number of molecules,

162
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:13,000
that itself is an interesting story.

163
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:16,000
But it's not the story I want to tell.

164
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,500
The story I want to tell

165
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:19,000
had to do with the mass

166
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,000
of a mole of material,

167
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:27,000
a mass of a given number, Avogadro's number of molecules,

168
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:32,000
that it came in discrete multiples

169
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:37,000
of the mass of a mole of hydrogen.

170
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
Now not exactly,

171
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:43,000
but close enough to a pretty good precision

172
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:48,000
are the mass of a mole of gobbledygook

173
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,000
is an integer multiple,

174
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:54,000
not three halves, not pi,

175
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
not some other silly number,

176
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,000
but some integer times the mass

177
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:03,000
of the same number of molecules of hydrogen.

178
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,000
That sort of suggested to Dalton

179
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
that there were building blocks,

180
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
that carbon, what is it, carbon eight?

181
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,000
Carbon twelve.

182
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:18,000
Carbon twelve had twelve units

183
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:22,000
of whatever hydrogen one had.

184
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
Hydrogen was one unit of stuff,

185
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
whatever that stuff was, carbon twelve,

186
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,000
or whatever the other numbers were.

187
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,000
So it seemed like things were being built up

188
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:35,000
out of basic units,

189
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
which basically had the same mass

190
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
as a hydrogen atom,

191
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
almost as though everything was made up

192
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
of units of hydrogen.

193
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:49,000
Dalton, I think, proposed something like that,

194
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,000
that there were basic units,

195
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:53,000
and those basic units had the mass

196
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:55,000
roughly of a hydrogen atom.

197
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
So that was the first bit of evidence,

198
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
and of course this was essentially right.

199
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,000
Today we understand,

200
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:05,000
let me just tell you why that's true

201
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:06,000
from today's perspective,

202
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:08,000
not to make a mystery out of it.

203
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:11,000
Everything is made out of atoms,

204
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,000
protons, neutrons, and electrons.

205
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
Electrons are very, very light

206
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
compared to protons and neutrons,

207
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,000
and in counting up the mass of an atom,

208
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,000
the electrons are not very significant.

209
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
An electron has about a mass of one two thousandth,

210
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
no, one two thousandth,

211
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
one two thousandth of the mass

212
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:36,000
of a proton or a neutron.

213
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
So electrons don't come into the equation,

214
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,000
they do come into the equation,

215
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
but only a very, very small term.

216
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Forget about them.

217
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Protons and neutrons constitute most of the mass,

218
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:49,000
almost all of the mass,

219
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
of ordinary material.

220
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,000
On the other hand,

221
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
protons and neutrons, surprisingly,

222
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
there's no, well, there is a good reason for it,

223
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:00,000
but at the time there was certainly no known reason.

224
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
In fact, protons and neutrons weren't known.

225
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
But protons and neutrons have about

226
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
the same mass as each other.

227
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
As I said, about two thousand times

228
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:12,000
the mass of an electron.

229
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,000
And so the mass of a molecule

230
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:19,000
is basically the mass of protons plus neutrons.

231
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,000
They have about the same mass,

232
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,000
and therefore the mass of a molecule

233
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
is an integer multiple

234
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:28,000
of the mass of a proton and neutron.

235
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:30,000
On the other hand, hydrogen is,

236
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:33,000
the nucleus of hydrogen is just one proton,

237
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
and so it did turn out that Dalton was right.

238
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
All materials have a mass which is

239
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,000
approximately, there's an approximation in there,

240
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
protons and neutrons don't have quite the same mass,

241
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:48,000
slightly different, less than a percent, incidentally,

242
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000
a tenth of a percent or even less,

243
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,000
whereas electrons are so light

244
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
that they don't come into it very much.

245
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:58,000
And so Dalton was right.

246
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
And it was the first, to my knowledge,

247
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
the first real evidence

248
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
that matter came in discrete units.

249
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:12,000
Now, molecules weren't atoms, of course.

250
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,000
It took a little while longer

251
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
to find out that molecules

252
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:18,000
were made up out of atoms,

253
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:21,000
and the atoms weren't just protons and neutrons or hydrogen,

254
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
that atoms themselves, the things we now call atoms,

255
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
that there were about a hundred of them,

256
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
a hundred different kinds.

257
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
This was, of course, the great triumph of chemistry

258
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:34,000
of the 19th century and early 20th century,

259
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,000
to identify all of the elements

260
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
that go into the periodic table up there.

261
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:43,000
Incidentally, the periodic table is not very periodic.

262
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:47,000
You know, if you really look at it,

263
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,000
it's a bit of a fake, the periodic table.

264
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:52,000
It's not very periodic.

265
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,500
But nevertheless, identifying all

266
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:57,000
those separate atoms up there,

267
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
the elements, the elements are in some things

268
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
which are composed of all the same kind,

269
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:03,000
you know that story,

270
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
composed of atoms,

271
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:07,000
and identifying the atoms,

272
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:10,000
and at the end of the identification of atoms,

273
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,000
roughly about a hundred of them,

274
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:16,000
less than a hundred occurring in nature,

275
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:19,000
92 of them to be precise,

276
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,000
well, more than that if you include isotopes,

277
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:26,000
but over a hundred different kinds of atoms,

278
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
and everything made up out of atoms.

279
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
So atoms, at the end of the 19th century,

280
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
the things we call atoms or elements

281
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:36,000
were the building blocks,

282
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:39,000
the elementary particles of nature.

283
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
Now of course it took another five years

284
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,000
after the turn of the century for Einstein

285
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,000
to do something that nailed,

286
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:50,000
really, really nailed the molecular theory of matter.

287
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:56,000
It wasn't until 1905 that Einstein explained in detail

288
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:58,000
how you could prove that matter

289
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,000
was really made out of particles,

290
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
but long before that,

291
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
chemists, physicists understood,

292
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,000
for the most part,

293
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:12,000
that everything was made out of these 92 elements.

294
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,000
So they were the elementary particles.

295
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
Now, sort of all hell broke loose

296
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:20,000
in the beginning of the 20th century,

297
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,000
very, very end of the 19th century,

298
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:27,000
when some discoveries were made.

299
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:29,000
The electron was discovered.

300
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:30,500
About three years, I think,

301
00:13:30,500 --> 00:13:32,000
before the turn of the century,

302
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,000
I don't know exactly when it was,

303
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:35,000
the electron was discovered,

304
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,000
and a number of other things were discovered,

305
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:40,000
but in particular, radioactivity was discovered.

306
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Radioactivity was the first real signal

307
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:52,000
of the thing which was later to become

308
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,000
nuclear physics,

309
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:58,000
and nuclear physics and particle physics,

310
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
were all the things that needed to be explained,

311
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,000
sort of there,

312
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
in a sort of tiny, tiny little version.

313
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,000
So let me just remind

314
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
you about radioactivity, just for fun.

315
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Who was it who discovered radioactivity?

316
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:16,000
I don't even remember.

317
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:17,500
I don't think it was

318
00:14:17,500 --> 00:14:19,000
Marie Curie who discovered radioactivity.

319
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:21,000
I don't think so.

320
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:23,000
Was it Becquerel?

321
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:25,000
I think it was Becquerel.

322
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,000
I don't think it was Marie Curie.

323
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
What she did was,

324
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:32,000
lots and lots of experiments to pin it down,

325
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:34,000
but it was Becquerel.

326
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:38,000
And he had a chunk of lead.

327
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
Don't ask me why he did this.

328
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:42,000
I do not know.

329
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,000
He had a chunk of lead,

330
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:45,500
and a little hole in

331
00:14:45,500 --> 00:14:47,000
the chunk of lead like that,

332
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,000
and some material down here.

333
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
Radioactivity.

334
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
I guess the first thing that happened

335
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,000
was he had some radioactive material,

336
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,000
presumably radium or something like it,

337
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:00,000
in his laboratory,

338
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:02,000
and he had a photographic plate,

339
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
and accidentally the photographic plate

340
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:08,000
happened to be near the material.

341
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:10,000
Not here, over here.

342
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:12,000
Material, photographic plate.

343
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And the photographic plate got ruined.

344
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:18,000
Ruined by the presence of the radioactive material.

345
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:22,000
The radioactive material just ruined,

346
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:25,000
you know, was like light shining on it,

347
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
and ruined the photographic plate.

348
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:29,000
Anybody else, or not anybody else, probably me,

349
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,000
would have just thrown away the plate and said,

350
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:33,000
ah, this is ruined, let's find another plate

351
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
and start the experiment over again.

352
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:38,000
But Becquerel realized he had discovered something.

353
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,000
He had discovered that radioactive materials

354
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:43,000
do something to the photographic plate

355
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:46,000
as if they had been illuminated by some radiation.

356
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:48,000
So he decided to study

357
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:50,000
that radiation a little bit better,

358
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:52,000
and he put the source of

359
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:54,000
it deep in a block of lead.

360
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:56,000
How he knew to use lead, I do not know,

361
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:59,000
but lead was a good substance because it's very dense.

362
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:01,000
And he put it into

363
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
a hole, drilled into the lead,

364
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:06,000
and then put his photographic plate out here,

365
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:11,000
and wanted to see whether it would illuminate

366
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
a single spot over here.

367
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
Everything was collimated by this hole.

368
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
He wanted to see whether it

369
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:23,000
would create a sharp little spot

370
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,000
as if something were coming up out of this hole.

371
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:28,000
And indeed it did.

372
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:30,000
So he got the idea

373
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:32,000
that a beam of some sort

374
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:36,000
was being ejected, or something was being ejected

375
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:39,000
by this radioactive material,

376
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:42,000
and being collimated along a beam.

377
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,000
That was the first particle beam.

378
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:46,000
That was the first beam of particles.

379
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
What was it? He had no idea what it was.

380
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:53,000
But then I guess a second fortuitous accident,

381
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:55,000
I think it was an accident, again,

382
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:57,000
I'm making up the history as I go along,

383
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:59,000
but it's close to the truth.

384
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:02,000
He happened to have a magnet in the laboratory.

385
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
And for some reason the

386
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,000
magnet was in a position here

387
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:09,000
where a magnetic field was created

388
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:13,000
near where these particles were being ejected.

389
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:16,000
And what happened when he put the magnetic field,

390
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,000
when he put the magnet near this,

391
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:23,000
is the beam split into three separate beams.

392
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
Three separate beams.

393
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:28,000
One went straight ahead,

394
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:33,000
just as if the magnetic field was not there.

395
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:36,000
One of them got deviated to the left,

396
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:39,000
and one of them got deviated to the right.

397
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:41,000
Left, right, right, left, whatever.

398
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:44,000
One deviated more than the other, in fact.

399
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
They were not symmetric.

400
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:50,000
And Becquerel, or somebody, whoever was around,

401
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:55,000
knew enough to realize that beams of force

402
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:58,000
were not the force of the magnetic field.

403
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:01,000
So the magnetic field is a force of force.

404
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:03,000
And it's a force of force.

405
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:04,000
And if you have a magnet,

406
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,000
and you have a charged particle,

407
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:09,000
the charged particle goes through the magnetic field

408
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:13,000
and either bends to the right or to the left,

409
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:16,000
depending on the sign of the magnetic field

410
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:19,000
and the charge of the particle.

411
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
So if the particle was a positively charged particle,

412
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,000
it would bend one way in the magnetic field.

413
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,000
And what Becquerel had found

414
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:29,000
is that there were three kinds of radiation.

415
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:31,500
One behaving as if it

416
00:18:31,500 --> 00:18:34,000
was composed of electrically neutral particles.

417
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:36,000
Which one was electrically neutral?

418
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,000
The one that wasn't deviated at all.

419
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,000
Of course, he didn't know they were particles.

420
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:44,000
All he knew was that some collimated effect happened

421
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:48,000
that illuminated the magnetic field.

422
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:51,000
And that was the first thing he found.

423
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:53,000
And then he found that the second thing he found

424
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:57,000
was the detector, the screen, the photographic plate.

425
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:00,000
One of them got deviated to the right

426
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:04,000
as if it were a negatively charged particle.

427
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:08,000
He called that component of the radiation,

428
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:10,000
he called that component beta.

429
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:12,000
The component that went straight ahead,

430
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:14,000
he called gamma.

431
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:17,000
And the component that deviated in the other direction

432
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:19,000
as if it were positively charged,

433
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,000
he called alpha.

434
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
These became the three components

435
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
of the three distinct kinds of radioactive effects,

436
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:31,000
the three distinct kinds of radioactivity.

437
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:37,000
Beta radioactivity, gamma and alpha.

438
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:43,000
Just again, I'm not interested in making suspense here.

439
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:44,000
Let me just tell you what they were.

440
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:46,000
You probably know what they were.

441
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:48,000
Many of you know what they were.

442
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:52,000
Beta was electrons, negatively charged particles.

443
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:55,000
Which were just the electrons

444
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:57,000
that had already been previously discovered

445
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,000
from cathode ray tubes and that kind of thing.

446
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,000
These were electrons coming out.

447
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:07,000
The alpha particles, we now understand,

448
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:09,000
and at that time there was no precedent for it,

449
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:11,000
that they are helium nuclei.

450
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Two protons and two neutrons stuck together.

451
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:16,000
Atomic number four.

452
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:20,000
Dalton, had he had access to helium,

453
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,000
which he didn't,

454
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:24,000
he would have said helium was number four

455
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:30,000
on his integer collection of materials.

456
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:34,000
And gamma are photons.

457
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Electrically neutral, no electricity at all.

458
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:41,000
And these three kinds of...

459
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:47,000
Now, I think he did...

460
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:49,000
Again, I don't remember the history,

461
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,000
but he might have.

462
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:55,000
And so, don't think you know.

463
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:56,000
But in that case,

464
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
the results were that

465
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:00,000
all of the electrons that the atom had

466
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:03,000
had a sufficiently dilute source

467
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,000
that these particles arrived,

468
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,000
one at a time,

469
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
at their destination.

470
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:09,000
And in that case,

471
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:10,000
he would not have seen

472
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:12,000
a bright spot over here.

473
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:14,000
He would have seen

474
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:15,000
blip,

475
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:16,000
blip,

476
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:17,000
blip,

477
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:18,000
blip,

478
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:19,000
illumination occurring,

479
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:20,000
or spots occurring,

480
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:23,300
And he might have said, oh, those are particles.

481
00:21:24,260 --> 00:21:26,630
Particles arriving one at a

482
00:21:26,630 --> 00:21:29,000
time, illuminating a screen discreetly.

483
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:32,260
He would have done exactly the

484
00:21:32,260 --> 00:21:34,200
same thing for the alpha particles.

485
00:21:34,480 --> 00:21:36,660
He would have found that the

486
00:21:36,660 --> 00:21:38,840
alpha particles arrived one at a time.

487
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:41,190
In other words, he could have used,

488
00:21:41,190 --> 00:21:42,460
he might have used, he probably did,

489
00:21:42,720 --> 00:21:45,220
used the screen here as a counter,

490
00:21:45,220 --> 00:21:47,720
analogous to a Geiger counter or something.

491
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:50,160
Whether he did or not, I don't know.

492
00:21:51,300 --> 00:21:54,140
But it's something you can imagine, that he

493
00:21:54,140 --> 00:21:56,980
detected the particles coming one at a time.

494
00:21:57,080 --> 00:21:59,220
That would certainly be feasible with a Geiger counter.

495
00:22:00,520 --> 00:22:05,340
And so, evidence that whatever this radiation is,

496
00:22:05,640 --> 00:22:07,250
it's coming in discreet little

497
00:22:07,250 --> 00:22:08,860
bundles that we could call particles.

498
00:22:09,440 --> 00:22:12,440
What about gamma? Same thing for gamma.

499
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:14,940
Gamma's coming one at a time.

500
00:22:15,160 --> 00:22:17,700
But at that time, Becquerel had no idea.

501
00:22:17,920 --> 00:22:21,920
Neither did anybody else what gamma was.

502
00:22:22,620 --> 00:22:25,120
It was uncharged. That was all that was known.

503
00:22:26,220 --> 00:22:32,020
And it illuminated the screen just as the others did.

504
00:22:32,620 --> 00:22:34,920
Okay. That was, as I said, in

505
00:22:34,920 --> 00:22:37,220
some sense, the first particle physics experiment.

506
00:22:38,120 --> 00:22:39,470
We'll come to some later

507
00:22:39,470 --> 00:22:40,820
particle physics experiments soon enough.

508
00:22:42,520 --> 00:22:47,120
Let's next talk about electromagnetic radiation.

509
00:22:47,720 --> 00:22:49,720
Ordinary electromagnetic radiation.

510
00:22:50,220 --> 00:22:53,720
Oh, well, I said I wasn't going to make suspense.

511
00:22:54,320 --> 00:22:57,920
Gamma is photons. Gamma is light.

512
00:22:58,120 --> 00:23:00,620
Gamma, well, it's very high energy light.

513
00:23:00,920 --> 00:23:06,920
But gamma is in some way connected to ordinary light.

514
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:09,420
So let's come to light.

515
00:23:09,720 --> 00:23:12,270
Gamma was the big mystery because there

516
00:23:12,270 --> 00:23:14,820
were no neutral particles known at that time

517
00:23:15,320 --> 00:23:15,920
that

518
00:23:16,080 --> 00:23:17,520
could account for the gamma radiation.

519
00:23:17,520 --> 00:23:19,520
So gamma was a mystery.

520
00:23:20,020 --> 00:23:25,020
And that mystery persisted until fairly

521
00:23:25,020 --> 00:23:30,020
late in the very early 20th century.

522
00:23:30,020 --> 00:23:31,020
Let's put it that way.

523
00:23:31,020 --> 00:23:34,020
Fairly late in the very early 20th century.

524
00:23:35,020 --> 00:23:40,020
It was, of course, Planck and Einstein, really Einstein,

525
00:23:40,020 --> 00:23:43,020
who were the first to

526
00:23:43,020 --> 00:23:46,020
understand that light comes in quanta,

527
00:23:46,020 --> 00:23:47,020
that light comes in photons.

528
00:23:47,020 --> 00:23:48,520
But let's go back.

529
00:23:49,520 --> 00:23:53,520
Light was sort of the strong, strong case

530
00:23:53,520 --> 00:23:57,520
for something which was not made of particles.

531
00:23:58,020 --> 00:24:01,020
Light was something which was clearly made of fields.

532
00:24:01,020 --> 00:24:03,520
It was made of the electromagnetic field.

533
00:24:04,020 --> 00:24:06,770
Okay, the electromagnetic field, electric

534
00:24:06,770 --> 00:24:09,520
fields and magnetic fields forming waves.

535
00:24:09,520 --> 00:24:13,020
When you shake a charge, waves get given off.

536
00:24:13,020 --> 00:24:16,020
The wave fields are continuous wave fields,

537
00:24:16,020 --> 00:24:16,520
at least according to,

538
00:24:16,520 --> 00:24:19,020
according to classical electrodynamics.

539
00:24:19,520 --> 00:24:21,520
And they give off waves

540
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:23,520
that propagate through space completely continuously.

541
00:24:24,020 --> 00:24:29,020
And Newton, of course, had thought that light was particles.

542
00:24:29,520 --> 00:24:32,020
But Newton, by that time, had

543
00:24:32,020 --> 00:24:34,520
been completely relegated to the dustbin,

544
00:24:34,520 --> 00:24:37,020
at least as far as theory of light went.

545
00:24:37,520 --> 00:24:39,770
There were many experiments, some

546
00:24:39,770 --> 00:24:42,020
of them done by Newton himself,

547
00:24:42,520 --> 00:24:46,020
that strongly said light is waves, not particles.

548
00:24:46,520 --> 00:24:48,520
So let's just talk about

549
00:24:48,520 --> 00:24:50,520
light a little bit, electromagnetic radiation.

550
00:24:53,020 --> 00:24:57,520
If you take electromagnetic radiation, it comes in waves.

551
00:24:58,520 --> 00:25:00,020
So if there's a source

552
00:25:00,020 --> 00:25:01,520
of electromagnetic radiation here, an antenna,

553
00:25:02,020 --> 00:25:04,770
some form of antenna emitting, it could

554
00:25:04,770 --> 00:25:07,520
be radio waves, it could be microwaves,

555
00:25:07,520 --> 00:25:10,270
it could be infrared, it could

556
00:25:10,270 --> 00:25:13,020
be light, it could be ultraviolet.

557
00:25:13,520 --> 00:25:15,520
An atom is a perfectly good,

558
00:25:15,520 --> 00:25:17,520
a good antenna, incidentally.

559
00:25:18,020 --> 00:25:21,020
It doesn't have to be a big macroscopic tower.

560
00:25:21,020 --> 00:25:23,020
An atom with a charge going

561
00:25:23,020 --> 00:25:25,020
around in a circle is an antenna.

562
00:25:25,520 --> 00:25:28,020
Antennas emit waves.

563
00:25:29,520 --> 00:25:32,020
And those electromagnetic waves, when they

564
00:25:32,020 --> 00:25:34,520
also fall on a photographic plate

565
00:25:35,020 --> 00:25:37,270
or other device which is sensitive

566
00:25:37,270 --> 00:25:39,520
to light or sensitive to radiation,

567
00:25:40,020 --> 00:25:44,020
will illuminate that, will illuminate that

568
00:25:44,020 --> 00:25:45,520
and turn it white or

569
00:25:45,520 --> 00:25:47,020
black, turn it black, I guess.

570
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:50,020
And that's in the character of light.

571
00:25:50,020 --> 00:25:53,020
Now how do we know that these things are waves?

572
00:25:53,020 --> 00:25:57,520
How can we tell that they're also

573
00:25:57,520 --> 00:26:02,020
not bullets shot out of the source here?

574
00:26:02,520 --> 00:26:05,770
So one thing you might do is do

575
00:26:05,770 --> 00:26:09,020
something very similar to what was done over here.

576
00:26:09,520 --> 00:26:11,520
Put an obstruction,

577
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:13,520
a little hole,

578
00:26:14,020 --> 00:26:17,770
and see whether the light is collimated exactly as if

579
00:26:17,770 --> 00:26:21,520
it were bullets being shot out of a gun here.

580
00:26:22,520 --> 00:26:24,020
If it was bullets, you would

581
00:26:24,020 --> 00:26:25,520
illuminate a little spot over here.

582
00:26:26,020 --> 00:26:29,020
And of course what happens is that

583
00:26:29,020 --> 00:26:32,020
you don't illuminate such a small spot.

584
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:35,020
You illuminate something which is fuzzier than that.

585
00:26:38,520 --> 00:26:40,520
You illuminate a fuzzy region.

586
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:42,020
But that in itself did

587
00:26:42,020 --> 00:26:43,520
not prove that light was waves.

588
00:26:44,520 --> 00:26:45,520
Not at all.

589
00:26:45,520 --> 00:26:48,770
You could say, well, just maybe when

590
00:26:48,770 --> 00:26:52,020
these particles go through this opening here,

591
00:26:52,520 --> 00:26:56,020
maybe they have little forces exerted on them

592
00:26:56,020 --> 00:26:59,520
by the edges of the hole here or whatever,

593
00:26:59,520 --> 00:27:03,020
which deflect them, some of them get deflected,

594
00:27:03,520 --> 00:27:06,020
and so maybe you get a more smeary picture,

595
00:27:06,020 --> 00:27:08,520
a more smeary image than you might have hoped for.

596
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:12,520
So it was not just that the beams got deflected,

597
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:13,520
the light beams got deflected,

598
00:27:13,520 --> 00:27:16,520
that in itself was not enough to

599
00:27:16,520 --> 00:27:19,520
argue for a particle structure to light,

600
00:27:19,520 --> 00:27:22,520
or sorry, a wave structure to light, I'm sorry.

601
00:27:22,520 --> 00:27:25,520
But you do something else, which is much

602
00:27:25,520 --> 00:27:28,520
more sensitive to the wave character of light.

603
00:27:28,520 --> 00:27:31,020
Here's the screen over here again.

604
00:27:31,020 --> 00:27:32,770
You open up two little holes,

605
00:27:32,770 --> 00:27:34,520
two little holes next to each other.

606
00:27:36,020 --> 00:27:38,520
If light was simply particles,

607
00:27:38,520 --> 00:27:40,770
what you would expect to find here

608
00:27:40,770 --> 00:27:43,020
is basically two smears of the same kind,

609
00:27:43,020 --> 00:27:46,020
just superimposed on top of each other,

610
00:27:46,020 --> 00:27:47,770
maybe a little extra dense

611
00:27:47,770 --> 00:27:49,520
in the center where they overlap,

612
00:27:49,520 --> 00:27:52,520
but just two smears, one the image of this

613
00:27:52,520 --> 00:27:55,520
hole, one the image of that hole, with nothing unusual.

614
00:27:55,520 --> 00:27:58,520
This of course is not what happens.

615
00:27:58,520 --> 00:28:02,520
What happens is each hole emits waves.

616
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:09,020
You could do the same trick with water waves.

617
00:28:09,020 --> 00:28:10,520
In fact, it's not hard to

618
00:28:10,520 --> 00:28:12,020
do the same trick with water waves.

619
00:28:13,020 --> 00:28:16,020
And the water waves interfere.

620
00:28:16,020 --> 00:28:18,020
If this is the high point

621
00:28:18,020 --> 00:28:20,020
of a wave coming out of here,

622
00:28:20,020 --> 00:28:22,020
and this is the low point of a wave,

623
00:28:22,020 --> 00:28:25,520
places where the high points combine

624
00:28:25,520 --> 00:28:29,020
from the two holes reinforce each other.

625
00:28:29,020 --> 00:28:32,520
Places where a high point from one hole meets

626
00:28:32,520 --> 00:28:36,020
a low point from the other hole cancel each other.

627
00:28:37,020 --> 00:28:39,520
And so the effect is to see when

628
00:28:39,520 --> 00:28:42,020
it hits the screen here, to see bands.

629
00:28:43,020 --> 00:28:47,020
The bands of positive reinforcement

630
00:28:47,020 --> 00:28:51,020
where the high points add,

631
00:28:51,020 --> 00:28:54,020
missing places with no light where

632
00:28:54,020 --> 00:28:57,020
the high points meet low points.

633
00:28:57,020 --> 00:29:00,020
That's an interference pattern.

634
00:29:00,020 --> 00:29:02,520
Interference pattern is a real signal

635
00:29:02,520 --> 00:29:05,020
of wave-like motion, of wave behavior.

636
00:29:05,020 --> 00:29:08,020
Waves, you can do this, as I said, with water.

637
00:29:08,020 --> 00:29:09,520
You just put your finger

638
00:29:09,520 --> 00:29:11,020
into water and wiggle two fingers,

639
00:29:11,020 --> 00:29:13,020
and the two waves, from the two ends,

640
00:29:13,020 --> 00:29:15,020
will spread out.

641
00:29:15,020 --> 00:29:19,020
Some places they'll reinforce, some places they'll cancel.

642
00:29:19,020 --> 00:29:25,020
And so rather peculiarly, but nothing terribly unusual,

643
00:29:25,020 --> 00:29:27,520
places which would have been illuminated by

644
00:29:27,520 --> 00:29:30,020
either of the two holes by themselves,

645
00:29:30,020 --> 00:29:33,020
there's destructive interference, they get canceled,

646
00:29:33,020 --> 00:29:37,020
and places you get constructive interference and they add,

647
00:29:37,020 --> 00:29:40,020
and you get extra intensity.

648
00:29:40,020 --> 00:29:42,020
That is the kind of thing,

649
00:29:42,020 --> 00:29:45,520
this interference property was the kind of thing

650
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:49,020
that really nailed the wave theory of light.

651
00:29:50,020 --> 00:29:52,020
So light was a wave.

652
00:29:52,020 --> 00:29:55,020
In fact, this did not occur after Newton,

653
00:29:55,020 --> 00:29:57,020
it really occurred before Newton.

654
00:29:57,020 --> 00:30:03,020
Huygens was a 17th century?

655
00:30:03,020 --> 00:30:06,020
Huygens must have been 17th century, but previous to Newton.

656
00:30:06,020 --> 00:30:07,020
Who? What?

657
00:30:07,020 --> 00:30:08,020
Thomas Young?

658
00:30:08,020 --> 00:30:09,020
Yeah.

659
00:30:09,020 --> 00:30:11,020
The physicist that demonstrated the interference.

660
00:30:11,020 --> 00:30:14,020
Yeah, yeah, but Huygens already had

661
00:30:14,020 --> 00:30:17,020
the basic ideas of wave propagation,

662
00:30:17,020 --> 00:30:19,020
and that's from the 1600s sometime.

663
00:30:19,020 --> 00:30:21,020
So this debate went back,

664
00:30:21,020 --> 00:30:24,020
and Newton had done many experiments himself,

665
00:30:24,020 --> 00:30:28,020
which should have been interpreted as interference,

666
00:30:28,020 --> 00:30:30,020
as interference, wave interference.

667
00:30:30,020 --> 00:30:31,020
But he didn't.

668
00:30:31,020 --> 00:30:33,020
In any case,

669
00:30:33,020 --> 00:30:38,020
after these experiments, Young's experiment, others,

670
00:30:38,020 --> 00:30:40,020
it was definitely confirmed,

671
00:30:40,020 --> 00:30:45,020
that light is made of waves.

672
00:30:45,020 --> 00:30:47,020
Okay, what kind of waves?

673
00:30:47,020 --> 00:30:49,020
Well, that took Maxwell.

674
00:30:49,020 --> 00:30:51,520
Maxwell realized that they were

675
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:54,020
waves of electric and magnetic field.

676
00:30:54,020 --> 00:30:57,020
You know what an electric and magnetic field is?

677
00:30:57,020 --> 00:31:00,020
An electric field, well, I,

678
00:31:00,020 --> 00:31:02,020
look it up if you don't know,

679
00:31:02,020 --> 00:31:04,020
electric and magnetic fields,

680
00:31:04,020 --> 00:31:06,020
and light is a wavy

681
00:31:06,020 --> 00:31:08,020
motion of electric and magnetic fields.

682
00:31:08,020 --> 00:31:10,020
First of all, light is a wave,

683
00:31:10,020 --> 00:31:15,020
and here's a wave moving down the axis.

684
00:31:15,020 --> 00:31:18,020
What is that wave a wave in?

685
00:31:18,020 --> 00:31:21,020
Well, it's a wave of electric field.

686
00:31:21,020 --> 00:31:25,020
Here the electric field is pointing down.

687
00:31:25,020 --> 00:31:29,020
Here the electric field is pointing up.

688
00:31:29,020 --> 00:31:32,020
Here the electric field is pointing down.

689
00:31:32,020 --> 00:31:35,020
Let's just draw a line through there.

690
00:31:35,020 --> 00:31:39,020
Alternating electric field up, down, up, down.

691
00:31:39,020 --> 00:31:41,020
And the whole thing moves

692
00:31:41,020 --> 00:31:43,020
off with the speed of light.

693
00:31:43,020 --> 00:31:46,020
The whole thing moves off with the speed of light.

694
00:31:46,020 --> 00:31:48,020
Electric field, incidentally, there's also a

695
00:31:48,020 --> 00:31:50,020
magnetic field attached to the thing.

696
00:31:50,020 --> 00:31:53,020
It's a complicated object.

697
00:31:53,020 --> 00:31:55,020
It has magnetic field also.

698
00:31:55,020 --> 00:31:59,020
The magnetic field is perpendicular to the electric field.

699
00:31:59,020 --> 00:32:05,020
And so it sticks out this way.

700
00:32:05,020 --> 00:32:06,520
And that's what a light wave

701
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:08,020
would look like if you could see,

702
00:32:08,020 --> 00:32:10,520
if you could sample its electric and

703
00:32:10,520 --> 00:32:13,020
magnetic field as it went past you.

704
00:32:13,020 --> 00:32:15,020
Of course, as it passes you,

705
00:32:15,020 --> 00:32:17,520
it will constantly alternate very rapidly

706
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:20,020
if it's an ordinary light wave.

707
00:32:20,020 --> 00:32:23,020
Much too rapidly for you to be able to see.

708
00:32:23,020 --> 00:32:26,020
But if it were an extremely long radio wave,

709
00:32:26,020 --> 00:32:28,020
very, very long radio wave,

710
00:32:28,020 --> 00:32:30,020
you might be able to see

711
00:32:30,020 --> 00:32:32,020
the field oscillating in front of you.

712
00:32:32,020 --> 00:32:34,020
And this is, as I

713
00:32:34,020 --> 00:32:36,020
said, what it would look like.

714
00:32:36,020 --> 00:32:37,020
It's a wave.

715
00:32:37,020 --> 00:32:41,020
Being a wave, it will exhibit interference patterns.

716
00:32:41,020 --> 00:32:46,020
And Maxwell had absolutely nailed the

717
00:32:46,020 --> 00:32:51,020
wave and the electromagnetic theory of light.

718
00:32:51,020 --> 00:32:54,520
So let's talk about waves a

719
00:32:54,520 --> 00:32:58,020
little bit before we talk about particles.

720
00:32:58,020 --> 00:33:01,020
Let's talk a little more about

721
00:33:01,020 --> 00:33:04,020
waves and the properties of waves.

722
00:33:04,020 --> 00:33:07,020
The first property of a wave that I want to...

723
00:33:07,020 --> 00:33:11,020
come to is the wavelength.

724
00:33:11,020 --> 00:33:15,020
Wavelength is simply the distance along the wave

725
00:33:15,020 --> 00:33:24,020
before you return one full cycle to the next wave.

726
00:33:24,020 --> 00:33:25,520
All right, so you start here

727
00:33:25,520 --> 00:33:27,020
and you go and you come back

728
00:33:27,020 --> 00:33:30,020
to the same exact kind of thing as over here.

729
00:33:30,020 --> 00:33:34,020
That's one cycle or one full wavelength.

730
00:33:34,020 --> 00:33:37,020
And wavelength, the symbol for wavelength is lambda.

731
00:33:37,020 --> 00:33:40,020
Greek lambda.

732
00:33:40,020 --> 00:33:41,020
Okay.

733
00:33:41,020 --> 00:33:43,020
Lambda for length.

734
00:33:43,020 --> 00:33:45,020
That's the wavelength.

735
00:33:45,020 --> 00:33:47,020
And it's measured in units of distance.

736
00:33:47,020 --> 00:33:49,020
It's measured in meters or it's measured in centimeters,

737
00:33:49,020 --> 00:33:52,020
whatever your choice of units are.

738
00:33:55,020 --> 00:33:58,020
Okay, so lambda equals wavelength.

739
00:33:58,020 --> 00:34:00,020
Wavelength, let's just call it wavelength.

740
00:34:00,020 --> 00:34:03,020
Another property is if you were to stand still

741
00:34:03,020 --> 00:34:05,020
and just watch the wave go past you,

742
00:34:05,020 --> 00:34:06,520
you go ahead and go up and down

743
00:34:06,520 --> 00:34:08,020
and up and down and up and down,

744
00:34:08,020 --> 00:34:10,020
it would have some frequency.

745
00:34:10,020 --> 00:34:12,020
How many cycles per second?

746
00:34:12,020 --> 00:34:15,020
This is not the length of the wave in space.

747
00:34:15,020 --> 00:34:19,020
It's kind of the number of cycles per second

748
00:34:19,020 --> 00:34:22,020
or perhaps even something simpler,

749
00:34:22,020 --> 00:34:24,520
the time that it takes to go

750
00:34:24,520 --> 00:34:27,020
through one cycle as it passes you.

751
00:34:27,020 --> 00:34:30,020
That could be called the period of the wave.

752
00:34:30,020 --> 00:34:32,020
Period.

753
00:34:32,020 --> 00:34:33,020
It's a time.

754
00:34:33,020 --> 00:34:35,020
It's measured in seconds.

755
00:34:35,020 --> 00:34:37,520
So, and a light wave

756
00:34:37,520 --> 00:34:40,020
has a very, very short period.

757
00:34:40,020 --> 00:34:42,020
Up and down and up and down extremely fast,

758
00:34:42,020 --> 00:34:44,020
10 to the minus 15 seconds or something, whatever.

759
00:34:44,020 --> 00:34:47,020
The longer the wavelength, the slower the period.

760
00:34:47,020 --> 00:34:50,020
The shorter the wavelength, the faster,

761
00:34:50,020 --> 00:34:54,020
the shorter the wavelength, the shorter the period.

762
00:34:54,020 --> 00:34:58,020
Okay, what's the connection between wavelength and period?

763
00:34:58,020 --> 00:35:00,020
Yeah.

764
00:35:00,020 --> 00:35:01,020
Right.

765
00:35:01,020 --> 00:35:05,020
So think about the wave moving past you one wavelength.

766
00:35:05,020 --> 00:35:07,020
How long, how far does it move?

767
00:35:07,020 --> 00:35:09,020
It's moved distance lambda.

768
00:35:09,020 --> 00:35:11,020
How long has it taken?

769
00:35:11,020 --> 00:35:13,020
It's taken the period.

770
00:35:13,020 --> 00:35:15,020
The distance that it moves divided by the

771
00:35:15,020 --> 00:35:17,020
time that it takes to move that distance

772
00:35:17,020 --> 00:35:19,020
is the velocity of the wave.

773
00:35:19,020 --> 00:35:23,020
For light, that would be the speed of light.

774
00:35:23,020 --> 00:35:24,520
If it's not a light wave,

775
00:35:24,520 --> 00:35:26,020
it might be moving with different speed.

776
00:35:26,020 --> 00:35:27,520
If it's a water wave,

777
00:35:27,520 --> 00:35:29,020
it would be much smaller speed.

778
00:35:29,020 --> 00:35:31,020
If it's a sound wave, it's a smaller speed.

779
00:35:31,020 --> 00:35:33,020
But for a light wave,

780
00:35:33,020 --> 00:35:35,020
the wavelength divided by the speed

781
00:35:35,020 --> 00:35:37,020
divided by the period

782
00:35:37,020 --> 00:35:39,020
is always equal to the speed of light.

783
00:35:39,020 --> 00:35:41,020
Whatever the wavelength is,

784
00:35:41,020 --> 00:35:43,020
the period is given in terms of the wavelength

785
00:35:43,020 --> 00:35:45,020
or the wavelength is given in terms of the period.

786
00:35:45,020 --> 00:35:47,020
So that's a fundamental relation.

787
00:35:47,020 --> 00:35:50,020
It's usually expressed a different way.

788
00:35:50,020 --> 00:35:53,020
The inverse of the period, one over the period,

789
00:35:53,020 --> 00:35:55,020
is called the frequency.

790
00:35:55,020 --> 00:35:59,020
It's the number of oscillations per second.

791
00:35:59,020 --> 00:36:02,020
The number of oscillations per unit time

792
00:36:02,020 --> 00:36:04,020
is called the frequency,

793
00:36:04,020 --> 00:36:07,020
and that's equal to one over the period.

794
00:36:07,020 --> 00:36:09,020
The faster the period, the shorter the frequency.

795
00:36:09,020 --> 00:36:11,020
And so you can also write this

796
00:36:11,020 --> 00:36:15,020
as the wavelength times the frequency

797
00:36:15,020 --> 00:36:18,020
is equal to the speed of light.

798
00:36:18,020 --> 00:36:20,020
So if I give you the wavelength,

799
00:36:20,020 --> 00:36:21,020
you can tell me the frequency.

800
00:36:21,020 --> 00:36:22,020
If I give you the frequency,

801
00:36:22,020 --> 00:36:25,020
you can tell me the wavelength by solving this equation.

802
00:36:25,020 --> 00:36:28,020
And that's the fundamental connection

803
00:36:28,020 --> 00:36:32,020
between wavelength and frequency.

804
00:36:32,020 --> 00:36:34,020
Now since one of the things

805
00:36:34,020 --> 00:36:35,520
that we really do want

806
00:36:35,520 --> 00:36:37,020
to teach you a little bit

807
00:36:37,020 --> 00:36:42,020
is the terminology that physicists use for things.

808
00:36:42,020 --> 00:36:46,020
And they tend not to use the terminology

809
00:36:46,020 --> 00:36:50,020
of cycles per second for frequency.

810
00:36:50,020 --> 00:36:52,020
They use something else.

811
00:36:52,020 --> 00:36:55,020
It's radians per second.

812
00:36:55,020 --> 00:36:56,020
What does that mean?

813
00:36:56,020 --> 00:37:02,020
Imagine a thing going around in a circle.

814
00:37:02,020 --> 00:37:04,020
It's going around in a circle

815
00:37:04,020 --> 00:37:06,020
with a frequency f.

816
00:37:06,020 --> 00:37:10,020
That means f times around the circle per second.

817
00:37:10,020 --> 00:37:12,020
Physicists tend to use,

818
00:37:12,020 --> 00:37:14,020
physicists and mathematicians,

819
00:37:14,020 --> 00:37:17,020
tend to use not the number of times

820
00:37:17,020 --> 00:37:18,020
you go around in a second,

821
00:37:18,020 --> 00:37:20,020
but the number of radians.

822
00:37:20,020 --> 00:37:23,020
Radian is about 57 degrees.

823
00:37:23,020 --> 00:37:25,020
It's an angle about that big.

824
00:37:25,020 --> 00:37:27,020
How many radians per second?

825
00:37:27,020 --> 00:37:29,020
And the relationship between

826
00:37:29,020 --> 00:37:32,020
the frequency in terms of cycles per second

827
00:37:32,020 --> 00:37:33,020
and the frequency in terms of cycles per second,

828
00:37:33,020 --> 00:37:36,020
the frequency in terms of radians per second

829
00:37:36,020 --> 00:37:38,020
is very simple.

830
00:37:38,020 --> 00:37:39,020
In terms of radians per second,

831
00:37:39,020 --> 00:37:42,020
we call it omega.

832
00:37:42,020 --> 00:37:45,020
And they're closely connected to each other.

833
00:37:45,020 --> 00:37:49,020
Omega is just 2 pi times the frequency.

834
00:37:49,020 --> 00:37:50,020
Why 2 pi?

835
00:37:50,020 --> 00:37:54,020
Because there are 2 pi radians in a circle.

836
00:37:54,020 --> 00:37:57,020
So frequency can be measured in either way.

837
00:37:57,020 --> 00:38:00,020
Physicists tend to use omega,

838
00:38:00,020 --> 00:38:03,020
except when they're writing elementary physics books,

839
00:38:03,020 --> 00:38:06,020
for undergraduate pre-med majors,

840
00:38:06,020 --> 00:38:08,020
in which case they use f.

841
00:38:08,020 --> 00:38:10,020
Okay?

842
00:38:10,020 --> 00:38:11,020
We're all physicists.

843
00:38:11,020 --> 00:38:12,020
We're all grown up.

844
00:38:12,020 --> 00:38:14,020
We're all, you know,

845
00:38:14,020 --> 00:38:16,020
so we can use omega

846
00:38:16,020 --> 00:38:19,020
like the world of physics does.

847
00:38:19,020 --> 00:38:24,020
Omega is the frequency of light measured

848
00:38:24,020 --> 00:38:26,020
not in cycles per second,

849
00:38:26,020 --> 00:38:27,020
but in radians per second.

850
00:38:27,020 --> 00:38:28,020
You say, where is the

851
00:38:28,020 --> 00:38:29,020
angle for a light wave going?

852
00:38:29,020 --> 00:38:30,020
Don't worry about where the angle is.

853
00:38:30,020 --> 00:38:31,020
Just divide frequency,

854
00:38:31,020 --> 00:38:33,020
just multiply frequency by 2 pi.

855
00:38:33,020 --> 00:38:35,020
And that defines omega.

856
00:38:35,020 --> 00:38:36,020
All right.

857
00:38:36,020 --> 00:38:37,020
They're proportional to each other.

858
00:38:37,020 --> 00:38:38,020
All right.

859
00:38:38,020 --> 00:38:43,020
So we can also write this then as,

860
00:38:43,020 --> 00:38:45,020
let's write it this way.

861
00:38:45,020 --> 00:38:46,020
Frequency, I'm going to write it,

862
00:38:46,020 --> 00:38:52,020
frequency is equal to c divided by lambda.

863
00:38:52,020 --> 00:38:55,020
And now I'm going to substitute for frequency

864
00:38:55,020 --> 00:38:58,020
omega divided by 2 pi.

865
00:38:58,020 --> 00:39:00,020
And what do we get?

866
00:39:00,020 --> 00:39:03,020
We get omega is equal to 2 pi.

867
00:39:03,020 --> 00:39:07,020
2 pi c over lambda.

868
00:39:07,020 --> 00:39:10,020
Fundamental equation of wave motion

869
00:39:10,020 --> 00:39:12,020
that the frequency measured in radians

870
00:39:12,020 --> 00:39:15,020
and the wavelength are related

871
00:39:15,020 --> 00:39:17,020
by 2 pi times the speed of light.

872
00:39:17,020 --> 00:39:19,020
This, of course, is true for any wave

873
00:39:19,020 --> 00:39:23,020
if you plug in the right velocity.

874
00:39:23,020 --> 00:39:26,020
Okay, we will use that equation from time to time.

875
00:39:26,020 --> 00:39:28,020
So get it down.

876
00:39:28,020 --> 00:39:31,020
Now, as I said,

877
00:39:31,020 --> 00:39:34,020
light comes in different wavelengths.

878
00:39:34,020 --> 00:39:36,020
And those different wavelengths characterize

879
00:39:36,020 --> 00:39:40,020
the different kinds of radiation.

880
00:39:40,020 --> 00:39:43,020
Radio waves are very long wavelengths.

881
00:39:43,020 --> 00:39:45,020
Meters are certainly more than,

882
00:39:45,020 --> 00:39:50,020
certainly more than microscopic lengths.

883
00:39:50,020 --> 00:39:53,020
Radio waves can be anything from, what,

884
00:39:53,020 --> 00:39:57,020
a few centimeters to 10 centimeters or something.

885
00:39:57,020 --> 00:40:00,020
I don't remember exactly where the radio spectrum begins.

886
00:40:00,020 --> 00:40:02,020
Hmm?

887
00:40:02,020 --> 00:40:05,020
It can go up to anything.

888
00:40:05,020 --> 00:40:08,020
Arbitrarily long wavelengths are called still radio waves,

889
00:40:08,020 --> 00:40:10,020
even though no radio could

890
00:40:10,020 --> 00:40:12,020
work on the basis of waves

891
00:40:12,020 --> 00:40:15,020
that had a wavelength of a billion light years.

892
00:40:15,020 --> 00:40:19,020
But still, they're still called radio waves.

893
00:40:19,020 --> 00:40:21,020
And where's the smaller, what's the smallest radio wave?

894
00:40:21,020 --> 00:40:23,020
I think about 10 centimeters.

895
00:40:23,020 --> 00:40:27,020
And it's a highly arbitrary division, of course,

896
00:40:27,020 --> 00:40:29,020
completely arbitrary.

897
00:40:29,020 --> 00:40:32,020
Smaller than radio waves, smaller wavelength.

898
00:40:32,020 --> 00:40:35,020
Microwaves, microwaves go from a few centimeters

899
00:40:35,020 --> 00:40:41,020
down to, what, a micrometer or something like that, micron.

900
00:40:41,020 --> 00:40:45,020
Smaller wavelength than microwaves.

901
00:40:45,020 --> 00:40:47,020
Infrared, infrared waves.

902
00:40:47,020 --> 00:40:49,020
And then from infrared waves,

903
00:40:49,020 --> 00:40:51,020
you have light waves, visible light.

904
00:40:51,020 --> 00:40:53,020
Visible light is a rather

905
00:40:53,020 --> 00:40:55,020
narrow range of frequencies or wavelengths.

906
00:40:55,020 --> 00:40:59,020
And then comes ultraviolet, shorter wavelengths.

907
00:40:59,020 --> 00:41:02,020
X-rays, gamma rays.

908
00:41:02,020 --> 00:41:05,020
Gamma rays are just exactly these objects here.

909
00:41:05,020 --> 00:41:08,520
Very, very short wavelength,

910
00:41:08,520 --> 00:41:12,020
extremely short wavelength radiation.

911
00:41:12,020 --> 00:41:14,020
And that's what Becquerel had

912
00:41:14,020 --> 00:41:16,020
discovered coming out of there.

913
00:41:16,020 --> 00:41:19,020
The only trouble is

914
00:41:19,020 --> 00:41:22,020
that Becquerel discovered discrete bumps,

915
00:41:22,020 --> 00:41:25,020
you know, discrete blips, one at a time,

916
00:41:25,020 --> 00:41:29,020
and not nice, continuous waves.

917
00:41:29,020 --> 00:41:34,520
Okay, that then brings us

918
00:41:34,520 --> 00:41:40,020
to the puzzle of quantum mechanics.

919
00:41:40,020 --> 00:41:42,020
Now, we're not going to go into

920
00:41:42,020 --> 00:41:44,020
it in any great depth, certainly not tonight,

921
00:41:44,020 --> 00:41:48,020
but let's just recount the history a little bit.

922
00:41:48,020 --> 00:41:53,020
Einstein and Planck realized for a variety of reasons,

923
00:41:53,020 --> 00:41:56,020
mostly thermodynamic properties of light,

924
00:41:56,020 --> 00:41:58,020
that Einstein, Planck, and Planck,

925
00:41:58,020 --> 00:42:01,020
Einstein, that light had to be thought

926
00:42:01,020 --> 00:42:04,020
of as being made up out of discrete,

927
00:42:04,020 --> 00:42:07,020
indivisible elements.

928
00:42:07,020 --> 00:42:13,020
He might have, it might have been an experimental discovery.

929
00:42:13,020 --> 00:42:15,020
In fact, in some sense,

930
00:42:15,020 --> 00:42:17,020
Becquerel's discovery was an experimental discovery.

931
00:42:17,020 --> 00:42:19,520
It's just he didn't realize the

932
00:42:19,520 --> 00:42:22,020
thing he was seeing was electromagnetic radiation.

933
00:42:22,020 --> 00:42:25,020
So I won't go through the actual history,

934
00:42:25,020 --> 00:42:27,020
but let's make up an imaginary history

935
00:42:27,020 --> 00:42:30,020
of how the discreteness of light might have been discovered.

936
00:42:30,020 --> 00:42:32,020
It could have been discovered this way.

937
00:42:32,020 --> 00:42:37,020
You, again, shine your light on a,

938
00:42:37,020 --> 00:42:40,020
you shine your light on a screen.

939
00:42:40,020 --> 00:42:42,020
And you illuminate the screen,

940
00:42:42,020 --> 00:42:44,020
and of course what you see

941
00:42:44,020 --> 00:42:46,020
is a nice continuous blob of light.

942
00:42:46,020 --> 00:42:49,020
It could either be an interference pattern,

943
00:42:49,020 --> 00:42:51,020
or it could just be a single hole,

944
00:42:51,020 --> 00:42:52,520
in which case it would just

945
00:42:52,520 --> 00:42:54,020
be a blob on the screen.

946
00:42:54,020 --> 00:42:56,020
Okay.

947
00:42:56,020 --> 00:42:58,020
But now you do the experiment differently.

948
00:42:58,020 --> 00:43:00,020
Here's your source of light.

949
00:43:00,020 --> 00:43:02,020
You put an obstruction in the way.

950
00:43:02,020 --> 00:43:04,020
The obstruction is a filter.

951
00:43:04,020 --> 00:43:06,020
The obstruction is a, not a filter, but a,

952
00:43:06,020 --> 00:43:10,020
a semi-transparent, semi-opaque

953
00:43:10,020 --> 00:43:14,020
thing which blocks out a certain percentage of the light.

954
00:43:14,020 --> 00:43:16,020
What happens over here?

955
00:43:16,020 --> 00:43:18,020
Well, the blob gets dimmer.

956
00:43:18,020 --> 00:43:20,020
Okay. It's not as intense.

957
00:43:20,020 --> 00:43:22,020
You make it thicker.

958
00:43:22,020 --> 00:43:24,020
It's even less intense.

959
00:43:24,020 --> 00:43:29,020
You see less light arriving per unit of time.

960
00:43:29,020 --> 00:43:31,020
And you make it even a little bit thicker.

961
00:43:31,020 --> 00:43:34,020
And at some point, all of a sudden,

962
00:43:34,020 --> 00:43:37,020
the character of what's here changes.

963
00:43:37,020 --> 00:43:40,020
And instead of seeing the blob,

964
00:43:40,020 --> 00:43:48,020
you see discrete events, little blips.

965
00:43:48,020 --> 00:43:51,020
Now, if you wait a long time,

966
00:43:51,020 --> 00:43:53,020
these little blips build up.

967
00:43:54,020 --> 00:43:56,020
And they build up to something

968
00:43:56,020 --> 00:43:59,020
which has exactly the same pattern

969
00:43:59,020 --> 00:44:01,020
as the blob had.

970
00:44:01,020 --> 00:44:04,020
So the blob in this case, then,

971
00:44:04,020 --> 00:44:07,020
is some sort of effect

972
00:44:07,020 --> 00:44:09,020
that has to do with lots of little blips.

973
00:44:09,020 --> 00:44:11,020
So many little blips that you can't recognize them

974
00:44:11,020 --> 00:44:13,020
as being individual.

975
00:44:13,020 --> 00:44:15,020
That's the blob.

976
00:44:15,020 --> 00:44:18,020
But if you attenuate the light

977
00:44:18,020 --> 00:44:20,020
and cut it down

978
00:44:20,020 --> 00:44:22,020
so that the intensity coming through here

979
00:44:22,020 --> 00:44:24,020
is really, really small,

980
00:44:24,020 --> 00:44:26,020
what you see is blips.

981
00:44:26,020 --> 00:44:28,020
This experiment can actually be done.

982
00:44:28,020 --> 00:44:30,020
It was not done in those early days.

983
00:44:30,020 --> 00:44:32,020
But you can imagine.

984
00:44:32,020 --> 00:44:35,020
And this is what Einstein had suggested

985
00:44:35,020 --> 00:44:39,020
really does happen in his photoelectric paper,

986
00:44:39,020 --> 00:44:43,020
that light comes through as absolutely discrete things.

987
00:44:43,020 --> 00:44:47,020
The motivation for it was thermodynamics

988
00:44:47,020 --> 00:44:48,020
and other things.

989
00:44:48,020 --> 00:44:51,020
But this might have been the form of discovery,

990
00:44:51,020 --> 00:44:54,020
discovering these individual blips,

991
00:44:54,020 --> 00:44:56,020
and then,

992
00:44:56,020 --> 00:44:58,020
the light is coming through.

993
00:44:58,020 --> 00:45:00,020
And this is what really would happen.

994
00:45:00,020 --> 00:45:04,020
So, something very, very confusing going on.

995
00:45:04,020 --> 00:45:06,020
Light is a wave.

996
00:45:06,020 --> 00:45:08,020
That had already been proved.

997
00:45:08,020 --> 00:45:13,020
In fact, if we put a screen over here

998
00:45:13,020 --> 00:45:17,020
with two little holes in it,

999
00:45:17,020 --> 00:45:19,020
two little holes in it,

1000
00:45:19,020 --> 00:45:23,020
we will again see light coming through

1001
00:45:23,020 --> 00:45:25,020
bit by bit.

1002
00:45:29,020 --> 00:45:31,020
One at a time.

1003
00:45:31,020 --> 00:45:33,020
And if we leave it up there a long time,

1004
00:45:33,020 --> 00:45:37,020
the blips will sort of fill in,

1005
00:45:37,020 --> 00:45:42,020
and what they will form is an interference pattern.

1006
00:45:42,020 --> 00:45:45,020
So it became clear,

1007
00:45:45,020 --> 00:45:48,020
clear but still very confusing,

1008
00:45:48,020 --> 00:45:51,020
that light is made up out of indivisible elements

1009
00:45:51,020 --> 00:45:53,020
called photons,

1010
00:45:53,020 --> 00:45:57,020
and that the wave character of the light

1011
00:45:57,020 --> 00:46:00,020
really represents, or the wave pattern,

1012
00:46:00,020 --> 00:46:03,020
really represents the probability

1013
00:46:03,020 --> 00:46:06,020
that the photon appears at different places.

1014
00:46:06,020 --> 00:46:09,020
In other words, it's randomly arriving blips,

1015
00:46:09,020 --> 00:46:11,020
but they arrive with a probability

1016
00:46:11,020 --> 00:46:13,020
in different locations,

1017
00:46:13,020 --> 00:46:16,020
which follows the pattern

1018
00:46:16,020 --> 00:46:19,020
that was established by the wave theory.

1019
00:46:19,020 --> 00:46:22,020
The wave theory gives you a wave theory of probabilities.

1020
00:46:23,020 --> 00:46:25,020
That's quantum mechanics.

1021
00:46:25,020 --> 00:46:27,020
We may have to talk about,

1022
00:46:27,020 --> 00:46:29,020
we will have to talk about quantum mechanics

1023
00:46:29,020 --> 00:46:31,020
a great deal more.

1024
00:46:31,020 --> 00:46:36,020
But this kind of experiment,

1025
00:46:36,020 --> 00:46:38,020
this kind of observation about light

1026
00:46:38,020 --> 00:46:43,020
was the first example of a connection

1027
00:46:43,020 --> 00:46:44,520
which is really in a sense

1028
00:46:44,520 --> 00:46:46,020
what this course is all about.

1029
00:46:46,020 --> 00:46:50,020
It's a connection, first of all,

1030
00:46:50,020 --> 00:46:53,020
between waves of any kind,

1031
00:46:53,020 --> 00:46:59,020
and particles.

1032
00:46:59,020 --> 00:47:02,020
They are not two different things.

1033
00:47:02,020 --> 00:47:05,020
Somehow, waves and particles

1034
00:47:05,020 --> 00:47:09,020
are two manifestations of the same thing.

1035
00:47:09,020 --> 00:47:11,020
We'll have to come back to that,

1036
00:47:11,020 --> 00:47:14,020
and we'll try to explain it perhaps again later.

1037
00:47:14,020 --> 00:47:18,020
Now I'm just filling in some early facts,

1038
00:47:18,020 --> 00:47:23,020
mostly just to set the stage.

1039
00:47:23,020 --> 00:47:26,020
Waves and particles,

1040
00:47:26,020 --> 00:47:29,020
at least when it came to light,

1041
00:47:29,020 --> 00:47:32,020
were somehow intimately connected,

1042
00:47:32,020 --> 00:47:33,520
and it didn't make sense

1043
00:47:33,520 --> 00:47:35,020
to say light is a particle,

1044
00:47:35,020 --> 00:47:36,520
or it didn't make sense

1045
00:47:36,520 --> 00:47:38,020
to say light is a wave,

1046
00:47:38,020 --> 00:47:41,020
but has manifestations of both.

1047
00:47:41,020 --> 00:47:46,020
All right, the situation only got more complicated

1048
00:47:46,020 --> 00:47:51,020
when electrons were studied.

1049
00:47:51,020 --> 00:47:53,020
Electrons are clearly particles.

1050
00:47:53,020 --> 00:47:55,020
Everybody knows electrons are particles.

1051
00:47:55,020 --> 00:47:57,020
There was no ambiguity about that,

1052
00:47:57,020 --> 00:47:59,020
no more ambiguity than there was

1053
00:47:59,020 --> 00:48:01,020
about whether light was a wave or not.

1054
00:48:01,020 --> 00:48:02,020
It was.

1055
00:48:02,020 --> 00:48:04,020
But yet, something funny.

1056
00:48:04,020 --> 00:48:07,020
Well, something funny also happened with electrons.

1057
00:48:07,020 --> 00:48:10,020
You could do exactly the same kind of experiment

1058
00:48:10,020 --> 00:48:12,020
with electrons. You can.

1059
00:48:12,020 --> 00:48:14,020
Today, this experiment can really be done.

1060
00:48:14,020 --> 00:48:16,520
At the time, it was

1061
00:48:16,520 --> 00:48:19,020
a bit of a thought experiment,

1062
00:48:19,020 --> 00:48:21,020
but equivalent experiments,

1063
00:48:21,020 --> 00:48:22,020
you'd have to put the holes,

1064
00:48:22,020 --> 00:48:23,020
you'd have to make a screen,

1065
00:48:23,020 --> 00:48:25,020
you'd put the holes much closer to each other

1066
00:48:25,020 --> 00:48:26,020
if you want to do it with electrons

1067
00:48:26,020 --> 00:48:28,020
for one reason or another,

1068
00:48:28,020 --> 00:48:29,020
and you send electrons through.

1069
00:48:29,020 --> 00:48:31,020
Of course they come through one at a time.

1070
00:48:31,020 --> 00:48:33,020
Everybody knew electrons were little particles

1071
00:48:33,020 --> 00:48:36,020
that came through one at a time.

1072
00:48:36,020 --> 00:48:39,020
What was totally unexpected is,

1073
00:48:39,020 --> 00:48:41,020
or would have been unexpected,

1074
00:48:41,020 --> 00:48:42,020
was that the electrons,

1075
00:48:42,020 --> 00:48:45,020
when you open two holes,

1076
00:48:45,020 --> 00:48:48,020
form an interference pattern.

1077
00:48:48,020 --> 00:48:51,020
So it wasn't just that light was funny.

1078
00:48:51,020 --> 00:48:54,020
Particles were funny in general.

1079
00:48:54,020 --> 00:48:59,020
Electrons exhibited wave properties.

1080
00:48:59,020 --> 00:49:02,020
Light exhibited particle properties.

1081
00:49:02,020 --> 00:49:06,020
In fact, had we taken the alpha particles,

1082
00:49:06,020 --> 00:49:08,020
which are much heavier than electrons,

1083
00:49:08,020 --> 00:49:10,020
much, much heavier than electrons,

1084
00:49:10,020 --> 00:49:12,020
8,000 times heavier than an electron,

1085
00:49:12,020 --> 00:49:15,020
much harder to do these kind of experiments with,

1086
00:49:15,020 --> 00:49:18,020
but send them through two little holes like that,

1087
00:49:18,020 --> 00:49:20,020
we also would see interference patterns

1088
00:49:20,020 --> 00:49:22,020
and interference patterns.

1089
00:49:22,020 --> 00:49:24,020
This has been done with objects

1090
00:49:24,020 --> 00:49:27,020
which are much, much bigger than helium nuclei,

1091
00:49:27,020 --> 00:49:28,020
namely buckyballs.

1092
00:49:28,020 --> 00:49:31,020
Buckyballs have been sent through

1093
00:49:31,020 --> 00:49:34,020
interference experiments like this

1094
00:49:34,020 --> 00:49:38,020
and seen to form the same kind of interference pattern.

1095
00:49:38,020 --> 00:49:41,020
